05437nam a22010095i 9780520924383DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20002001cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209243837 a10.1525/97805209243832doi  a(DE-B1597)519528  a(OCoLC)49570129  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDC256.8 7aHIS0100002bisacsh04a944.062211 aKroen, Sheryl, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPolitics and Theater :bThe Crisis of Legitimacy in Restoration France, 1815-1830 /cSheryl Kroen. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2000] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (408 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies on the History of Society and Culture ;v4000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Staging Monarchy in a Postrevolutionary World -- tPart I. Politics as Theater -- t1. The “Counterrevolutionary” State and the Politics of Oubli (Forgetting) -- t2. The Missionaries: Expiation and the Resacralization of the King’s Two Bodies -- t3. Competing Commemorations: The Problem of Performing Monarchy -- tPart II. Theater as Politics -- t4. “Practicing” Politics in an Age of Counterrevolution -- t5. Popular Anticlericalism: Defining the Sacred in Postrevolutionary France -- t6. Tartufferie -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMoliére's anticlerical comedy Tartuffe is the unique prism through which Sheryl Kroen views postrevolutionary France in the years of the Restoration. Following the lead of the French men and women who turned to this play in the 1820s to make sense of their world, Kroen exposes the crisis of legitimacy defining the regime in these years and demonstrates how the people of the time made steps toward a democratic resolution to this crisis. Moving from the town squares, where state and ecclesiastical officials orchestrated their public spectacles in favor of the monarchy, to the theaters, where the French used Tartuffe to mock the restored monarch and the church, this cultural history of the Restoration offers a rich and colorful portrait of a period in which critical legacies of the revolutionary period were played out and cemented. While most historians have characterized the Restoration as a period of reaction and reversal, Kroen offers convincing evidence that the Restoration was a critical bridge between the emerging practices of the Old Regime, the Revolution, and the post-1830 politics of protest. She re-creates the atmosphere of Restoration France and at the same time brings major nineteenth-century themes into focus: memory and commemoration, public and private spheres, politics and religion, anticlericalism, and the formation of democratic ideologies and practices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDemocracyzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aLegitimacy of governmentszFrance. 0aMonarchyzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aanticlerical comedy.  aanticlericalism.  aclerics.  acomedy.  acultural history.  acultural studies.  adauphin.  ademocracy.  aecclesiastical officials.  aeurope.  afrench catholicism.  afrench comedy.  afrench history.  afrench revolution.  agovernment.  ahistory.  aking.  amonarchy.  apolitical engagement.  apolitical legitimacy.  apolitics.  apostrevolutionary france.  aprotest.  apublic spectacles.  aregime.  areign.  areligion.  arepresentative government.  arepublic.  arestoration.  arestored monarch.  arevolutionary period.  asatire.  asocial commentary.  atartuffe.  atheatricality.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gr